<subSubSection id="C300A1C27952FF9EBEF47D17CD79FCC2" box="[197,1289,770,796]" pageId="11" pageNumber="50" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BA5F2497952FF9EBEF47D17CD79FCC2" blockId="11.[151,1436,152,912]" box="[197,1289,770,796]" pageId="11" pageNumber="50">
<emphasis id="B96E2E5B7952FF9EBEF47D17C921FCC2" bold="true" box="[197,337,770,796]" pageId="11" pageNumber="50">Etymology.</emphasis>
From Latin 
<emphasis id="B96E2E5B7952FF9EBFD47D17CA52FCC5" box="[485,546,770,795]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="50">furca</emphasis>
= fork, in reference to the furcated projection of male tergite 8.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C300A1C27952FF9EBEF47D3DCA6AFC4E" pageId="11" pageNumber="50" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BA5F2497952FF9EBEF47D3DCA6AFC4E" blockId="11.[151,1436,152,912]" pageId="11" pageNumber="50">
<emphasis id="B96E2E5B7952FF9EBEF47D3DC921FC9C" bold="true" box="[197,337,808,834]" pageId="11" pageNumber="50">Discussion.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C1A89CA7952FF9EBF6B7D3CCA12FC9C" authorityName="Rafael &amp; Cumming" authorityYear="2009" box="[346,610,809,834]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Macrostomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="furcatus">
<emphasis id="B96E2E5B7952FF9EBF6B7D3CCA12FC9C" box="[346,610,809,834]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="50">Macrostomus furcatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from all other species of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C1A89CA7952FF9EBA297D3CCCB9FC9C" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1805" box="[1048,1225,809,834]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Macrostomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferrugineus">
<emphasis id="B96E2E5B7952FF9EBA297D3CCCB9FC9C" box="[1048,1225,809,834]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="50">M. ferrugineus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group by tergite 8 ending in a blunt bifid distal projection, by the shape of the posterior lobe of the cercus, and by the serrated apex of the hypandrium.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
